context_text: I strongly didn't believe what I was told because when I asked, the girl gave me a look like she knew that I wouldn't be accommodated but she still asked someone was there anymore chicken and the guy immediately said no but it was in a way that showed he just didn't want to cut any or grill any. Extremely disappointing as me and my friends had really wanted Felipe's. I had ordered 5 chicken quesadillas but had to cancel one of them because I refused to eat dry chicken. My friends still got their's as they were really hungry and didn't want to go some place else. I went to Five Guy's next door where I was guaranteed hot, fresh food.
First and last visit here. I worked in KFC management when I was younger. What goes on in this restaurant, I'm not sure. Standards are hard to find.

Earlier today my friend suggested we go to Roy's for some brisket. I had been here before to get beer but had never had the food. So I wanted to try the best they had to offer so I got a half rack of ribs, and order of brisket, three sides, a drink and a pack of cigarettes... $27. I couldn't believe how little I was paying. So anyways we head home and go to town. The ribs fall off the bone, the brisket melts in your mouth, and I'm like a pig in shit. My friends were getting annoyed with how much I was talking about it. After cleaning my plate, I knew I had to try more.

The carbonara and salmon pasta were both dry and bland, adding salt and pepper somewhat made it good. The salmon in the pasta are like flakes that was mixed in the sauce and they were not a lot. The lobster risotto was okay. Again, nothing wow about it and I also think there was not enough lobster meat in it. All dishes were not finished and were taken home to be recooked for tomorrow. We do not mind waiting especially when the place is full but earlier was different. I do not think I will be back. Carbonara, lobster risotto, salmon pasta + tip cost $78.

He knows his stuff. But I digress. Onto the food:

Dan Dan noodles. I know, I know, a lot of people have reviewed these. And trust me, they are not steering you wrong.

The food was amazing and l loved the green sauce, but I totally whiffed on my order. I thought I ordered the Paneer Butter Masala entree, but mistakenly ordered the paneer tikka appetizer. It was still very good, but my heart was set on some Indian comfort food, cheese cooked in a hearty creamy tomato sauce. Instead I got grilled cottage cheese and veggies which is more of a appetizer.

I got the Pad Thai, and it tasted like General Tso's sauce mixed in with noodles - not like any Pad Thai I've had before, so it was very disappointing. Beef was good, though. We came on a Saturday night with just our party of 5, and it took longer than usual to get our orders and our food.

Well they were refreshing alright; basically water, with super sweet apple and strawberry flavoring not one piece of fresh fruit, a splash of Bacardi and NO mint. Did not taste good at all. For dinner I ordered the cold gazpacho soup, which was very tasty and fresh, so I was pleased with my first selection. On the other hand the tomato and mozzarella salad was very disappointing. The tomatoes were ok, but there was literally a handful of quarter sized pieces of mozzarella alongside the salad.

My oldest son and I decided to check this place out for an early dinner before he took off for small group at church. The hibachi was good (not great), don't get me wrong, nothing bad, I just don't understand why they don't put bacon in the fried rice out here. The highlight of the evening however, was the tornado roll: a spicy tuna roll roped with an amazing melted topping that included spicy crab, scallops, and some kind of cheese (cream cheese maybe)? Oh my goodness...I'll be back for that roll if nothing else!!!

A couple of months ago, you needed a reservation almost every night of the week. I think it was about 30% full when we were there. I had a "pork belly" salad, and it had 2 chunks of pork belly on it....probably about the same weight as 2-3 strips of bacon, I guess. Were those two chunks yummy? Yes. Gee, thanks... I've never done this before...I heard the phrase "that doesn't have bread under her breath" more than once. She said "pot roast doesn't have bread in it" and I knew then that I wasn't going to be able to trust anything she said...so I just got that pork belly salad. And then it had a special garnish on top of fried onions that wasn't in the printed description. Fried in flour, of course.
There was lack of Taste of wing sauce. We ended up leaving almost 1/3 of it. Spicy rice cake was good and garden salad was ok

Then to the ramen, thank god they had corn which made it a tad bit better but the miso flavor was just lacking. I was really not impressed and didn't even finish my bowl... The second time I came back, we had the spicy kimchi ramen special on the back. Once again, not that tasty, maybe it's the broth. On top of that, the manager/waitress was yelling at one of the new employees in Chinese (which I understood) which made me feel terrible for him and enjoyed my meal less.
Yakitori Boy has good happy hour prices and selection. It was nice to get small dishes and try a lot of different stuff. The taste was ok for me.

Overall I wasn't thrilled, I didn't know what to expect here other than Korean food, which I was excited about. I have to say the food was tasty. The only issue having split an appetizer, and ordering the bulgogi for myself and bibimbap for my wife was that I left hungry. My wife seemed happy with the portion size of the bibimbap. The portion size of bulgogi and serving of rice (which you have to order separately) May have been fine if it came with all the traditional accoutrements. Another peeve I have is with the style of business.

I had Nina's 2 years ago and it was delicious. Unfortunately I had a sweet tooth last night and walked to Nina's. I ordered a waffle with 2 scoops of salted caramel ice cream with the pastry cream and whip cream, firstly he barley put any sauce on it that I paid for and totally skimped on the whip cream but what was really disturbing the flavor of the ice cream It had an old kick to it like it sat there through the winter or something. Normally I love salted caramel but last night all I was left with was a bitter taste. It cost me $10.

If you're looking for dim sum in Philly, I would only recommend Dim Sum Garden. Make sure you get there before the crowd on the weekend lunch and dinner hours, or else you'll be waiting in a long line to get a table (which speaks volumes). Any trip to Dim Sum Garden is incomplete without the soup dumplings - make sure you try these, and eat them the right way if you want to actually enjoy it. Our group ordered a lot of food and we ended up really full. The best part was that the total only came out to $40 between 4 of us.
Juicy Lucy's burger was yummy, but truth be told, for me to be totally wowed by a burger joint it's gotta go above and beyond. Above, yes, Juicy Lucy's is above average - but beyond. Well, no.

We went at noon on a Sunday, they just opened at 11:30 so there was just another 2 tables there, so we got seated fast. One thing that hit me right away is what a huge menu they have with both Malaysian and Chinese cuisine, so if it's your first time here, you may be overwhelmed with all the choices. My parents ordered fish congee and chow mein, while I went for the pork chops and rice. When mine came, I was a bit disappointed, as I was expecting some kind of marinated pork chop. What I got was 2 breaded pork chops, white rice (which actually was lots), canned corn with couple pieces of broccoli, and a type of tartar sauce(?) on the side. It wasn't what I expected and was very plain, as well didn't start off well, as I found a piece of hair in the rice. My parents found the congee a bit watery, and still think the best congee is at Hong Kong Bakery. The chow mein was good though, nothing out of this world, but one of those things that is always a good standby. I noticed that the Malays

now currently in Atlanta, Georgia and I'm extremely missing this spot. One of a kind! Don't miss out and don't forget to order a fried spring roll with dinner. They are not soaked in grease and sooo dang tasty!
Samosas were good, but that was about it. Butter chicken was ok. Saag paneer was most disappointing - watery and bland. Overall, far from the best.

I usually come here to pick up pozole or menudo for takeout. However there staff is really rude over the phone as they where when I picked up my order. I placed an order of menudo for picked up gave them my name and told me they where out.

Funny, they have been here several times and never complained and where I live is as safe as or safer than their restaurant location. Then the driver got lost even though she was given detailed instructions so the food was cold. Finally, I would NOT recommend the lasagna. It was filled with spinach with white cheese melted on top of it and was dry and burned. And absolutely no red sauce or cheese filling in site.

The bartender and I worked out something and made a custom made drink with lychee and gin and it was so delicious . I realized it was an Asian fix ion type of spot so they are mixing in both sides in their food . I had the pad Thai and a chicken satay which was so moist and delicious . The pad Thai was expensive $16 for a bowl that wasn't that big and the satay $6 . A bit overpriced ...

The order of the Delco pizza universe is restored. But what will set Marco's apart from the rest of the purveyors of pretty much the same pizza everywhere else? Marco's offers Brooklyn Square Pie, and chicken shawarma. That's a good start. I brought home a square pie with broccoli and pepperoni for the family and a chicken shawarma wrap for me tonight. And the verdict.... This is where I have a quandary.

The pig's foot was very good and I was pleased since this came highly recommended. The snapper was also very good, moist, tasty, but the vegetables which accompanied the fish did not seem to go very well. Then came dessert, a frozen Grand Marnier souffle and a pistachio creme something. We ended up not finishing the souffle, as we were both stuffed. Some espresso and some macaroons from the chef and we were all done. The staff was pleasant and polite and genuinely helpful.

The soup was a little too early for my taste, and there was a very small amount of meat and potatoes in the dish itself, with too many noodles. My parents frequently cook noodle soup back home, and I must say that I've had much better from my own kitchen. I wish that I could have sampled the peking duck, which Sang Kee is apparently known for. I got a small taste of the scallion pancakes and while the flavors were delicious, I was again put off by how oily the dish was. Good for a filling dinner as I was full for the rest of the night, but Sang Kee did not impress my palate.

New management has not been an improvement. The menu remains similar but the recipes are definitely lower quality- from the rice to the pita to the meat. The tabouli no longer has lemon juice, the meat came out lukewarm, the pita was hard and unpleasant. I no longer recommend this as a lunch spot.

Came here expecting some good local Mexican food, left disappointed. The service could've been better, as our waitress gave us our food then disappeared for more than 30 minutes and had us have to go up and ask for the check. I asked for no cilantro on my taco, but it was covered in cilantro when I got it. Since this is a Mexican restaurant, I can't really knock them for that. The food was the most disappointing part. I got the enchilada and taco combo platter, which came with rice and beans. While the portion size was amazing, I could not say the same for my actual food. The beef inside my enchilada was burnt, and the entire thing was under a thick layer of greasy cheese. The fish inside my taco was so bland that if I hadn't known it was fish, it could've been anything. The rice and beans were fine but not enough to save my meal. While the meal and service were not that great, this restaurant has a great interior design and portions.

If I'm happy, they make me overjoyed. I take houseguests here, which I think is high praise. I love the katsu sauce. I love the fries. I love the bar (the stools are short, so as a short girl, I don't feel like I'm on a highchair).
It's just okay. The food is simply AMAZING! The creme brulee french toast is to die for... as are the omelettes and the rosemary potatoes. We were able to get a table outside, which was perfect.

Beef Haw Fun, what's fun about chewy beef in a bowl of GREASY noodles. I don't recall asking for extra GREASY Basil fried rice. Satay chicken cooked over 1000° wood burning grill, thigh meat that was GREASY, mushy, and no char at all. I can't really say much for the service either. I had high hopes for this place but was extremely disappointed.

It's not. The food tastes amazing. I had the onion tart, grilled filet, creme brulee, bread pudding, and a French 75. My friend got the lemonfish, all were fantastic. Our servers Phillip and Sarah were also wonderful.

Then, not long after this, we were informed that sliced pork was again available. Not sure how that happens in the span of 10 minutes. As if all this weren't enough, the server showed up again to inform us they were out of ribs. More order changes... When our orders did finally show up, we were short one.

It wasn't bad, but wasn't what I was expecting, but the drink was only $2 for the happy hour special so it was a good deal. Sloppy Hoggs is a bbq joint and known for their huge, crazy portions of meat. While I debated getting the pulled pork sandwich I settled for the mini red beans and rice with cornbread. Really they sold me at cornbread. The read beans and rice was really good, a little spicy, and even though I didn't see it listed on the menu it was served with some chicken that had a light smoked flavour.

Food was mediocre. Ordered a taco salad no Guacamole..It was LOADED!!!! I am allergic to avocados....What is this a communication error??? And what was up with beanie weenies, was that a dis to gringos?

portion size is pretty good too. we ended up getting a box. -Curry: started with an "M" something curry, and is listed below the red and green curry. basically it's a Yellow curry. coconut milk, chicken, potatoes.
All too sweet... I ordered Mapo tofu. But I got some sweet fried tofu with lots of broccoli. I asked it that really was Mapo and it really was.

Overall, not an amazing experience, but not bad. I wouldn't seek it out again, but if someone wanted to go I wouldn't be opposed. Might try something else on the menu--they also have tacos and tortas.

We sat for nearly 10 minutes before we met our server. They have a nice variety on the menu. The tempura veggies/seafood are very good. The gyoza and crab puffs (Rangoon) are not very good. Tom Yum soup lacks that familiar tang. None of the rolls were exciting with flavor. Just all very "meh."  No issues with freshness as the fish seemed fine. The Thai Curry was a hit, with the veggies in it being tempura fried. Very unique and delicious. Entrees for 5 people came out at different times, one was just raw fish and it took the longest. Tempura cheesecake was wildly delicious. The worst part was that we were seated near the end of the hallway that lead to the restrooms (I assume.). We lived with a putrid smell all night.

For the price I paid I wouldn't order that again. I ordered the lentil walnut pate with a baguette for us to start, and a lemongrass minty vermicelli bowl for a main. My one friend ordered the pulled jackfruit enchilada, while the other ordered the laska soup. For sure my favourite was the lentil walnut pate...rich and nutty it tasted comforting on the cold spring day. My lemongrass minty vermicelli bowl was good, but again was advertised as spicy and I felt that it was a bit underwhelming.

The TV in the booth and charging station is a nice touch. The Cajun chicken pasta dish was good and the funnel fries with chocolate and strawberry sauce was a great little dessert. Service was really good as well.

This is like the Long's of the southside (yes I know there is a Long's on Southport but I'm an Indy native so don't judge). They carry delicious donuts that are pretty damn good. I love the selection of donuts they have, but they have a very nice variety of cakes, cookies, brownies, and coffee cakes. The coffee cakes came in a few varieties which would be good if you're hosting a brunch or some type of shower. I think the prices are very comfy with what they offer.

Asian Infusion type restaurant. I like their spicy California rolls and their happy hour prices. I get the Tom Kha Gai soup for $4 and add rice to make it a meal. As usual a lot of these restaurants don't use chicken thighs or dark meat, but rather thin slices of chicken breasts for their chicken. It seems like in Idaho..

The ice cream flavors are unique and delicious. The quality is premium and smooth. The shop smells heavenly, especially since they're constantly making waffle cones while you order. The booze ice cream flavors are a definite must try mixed with the nonalcoholic flavors. They do ask for I.D.

While small, the food is OH SO GOOD! Their naan is fresh made, so allow a little time for it to come out. I really liked their Butter chicken, it was rich and flavourful. My guys both had the chicken Tikka masala, hot. They had tears in their eyes and very happy bellies.

Delivery was pretty quick and the delivery person was very friendly. I will order again without a doubt. I ordered curry and larb gai. The larb in appearance was not what im used to but it was spot on in flavor. Its sad to see two recent less than stellar reviews one from someone who states that they dont care for unamerican food...but complains about the spice. FYI thai is notoriously spicy.
It was really good. A bit sweet maybe, but everything was excellent. We loved the Tom Kar soup (what they call Tom Kha Kai) and coconut rice so much, we bought extra to take home!

We shared an artisan cheese and salad for an appetizer. The cheese paired perfectly with the yummy bottle of wine we brought (I love BYOBs!!!). For dinner I had the Striped Bass and my husband had the Short Rib Ragu. The fish was cooked perfectly and the sauce was delicious. My husband liked the Ragu, but tired of it quickly. It was delicious but super hearty and filling. There's only so much short rib you can eat.

Had an enjoyable lunch at Otaku but the ramen was not quite up to New York standards. Nevertheless a welcome change from Nashville hot chicken and fries. Started off with gyoza (slightly bland with a super sour sauce) and okonomiyaki, their Sunday special. Between 4 people we still left about a quarter uneaten. Smelled a little fishy but tasted pretty good.

All their food is a bit oily & has a lot of garlic, but damn it's so good! - Oil Splashing Noodles are my few favorite! - Their Orange Chicken has a spicy kick to it! - When you order wontons to go the container is overflowing with wonton dumplings!!! The plain broth is the way to go, when I ordered the oily ones they were too oily, but tasted great when I added them to 2 cups of chicken broth at home, worked well to to dilute the oil and keep the chili flavor.

the restaurant is very nicely decorated. asian-y, but without being over the top ridiculous brothel-y, and definitely not gaudy like the fancy chinese restaurants in chinatown. we had the duck ceviche, marinated cabbage, congee, spareribs, salt crusted branzino, and hot pot. spareribs are quite tasty. the branzino was melt-in-your-mouth perfect (for $55, it had better be!).

Relaxing and quiet music. My coffees were always good. I loved the Vietnamese iced coffee. I've never had it before and had to look up online what to do with it, once the barista brought it to the table (I didn't know about the condensed milk sitting on the bottom). Otherwise, always great service.

You're probably wondering why I am giving them 4 stars if I have all these wonderful things to say. I have been a couple of times, service is definitely dependent on the time you go and the server you get. I have yet to have an entree I was wowed by; I've tried the tandoori salmon, the Honey butter chicken sandwich, and the pesto BLT. And last, but certainly not least, there is no such thing as getting bang for your buck at Louie's. My bill is always far more than I expected to pay for what I've ordered.

To really enjoy this place you have to expect that there will be a wait for your table sometimes 10 minutes or sometimes over an hour all dependent on what time of day and what day of the week you choose to go because they don't reservations. But if you go with this in mind and are willing to wait either on the benches outside or across the street at New Wave then you're ahead of the game. Whenever I eat here I always order the mussels sauteed (I think they're actually lightly floured and then pan fried), the grilled octopus, the shrimp scampi and the baba ganoush from the small plates section and then typically we'll order a platter to share. You can rarely go wrong if you choose one of the specials for the night. I also love the endless grilled pita they give you dipped in the oil that's left over from the shrimp scampi.

The four of us had a table right next to the fire place- perfect ambiance for a post holiday dinner. We all loved our food. I had the capellini carbonara with pancetta cream sauce and it was perfectly cooked and had awesome flavor. My only gripe is that everything is a la carte. To me, a chicken parm entree just isn't complete without a side of pasta!

California wrap was loaded with avocado and turkey. And Black Jack chicken sandwich was delicious. Waffle fries are also good and generously portioned. It's a fun place to go watch sports on tv or before a Pelicans game. Good for families.

These are the staples I always order. The ambiance is fun with music in the bar area or a little quieter in the back area. Sunday brunch is a great time to sit outdoors in the nice weather and enjoy the delicious quiche, seafood crepes and apple churros. The service tends to be pretty slow and they commonly make mistakes, but the upside is you end up with some items you may not have ordered so you can try more. They always fix their mistakes and ensure your experience is great.

Very filling. We ended our meal with dessert. Baklava...amazing cinnamon flavor and not honey drenched like the baklava I've had so many times before. We also shared the Knafeh--a heavenly blend of baklava and cheescake. Very rich and very good. The ONLY problem I had with Ranoush was our server.

So I come here for the Korean food and it's my favorite in town, not that there are many other options in town. The menu is limited, but I've been happy with what I get. Bibimbap comes in a generous silver bowl with lots of goodies and they will substitute tofu in place of meat if you're vegetarian. The ddubbokki is an enormous portion, can feed 2 people. It's served in a big bowl with rice cakes, fish cakes and mussels, with a hotplate flaming underneath.

Had too much sugar on the top but it was absolutely great to have to top the meal off with. It comes in a cup with possible condensed milk over it so it doesn't come dry like the other restaurants. ***We also ordered the Papaya Salad with sticky rice but it didn't come out but the waiter (who is not related to the owners) still tried to charge us for it. So check your bill before paying!!!***

We spent a total of 2 hours at this restaurant. Most of it was waiting.

Despite Domino's being a widespread pizza chain, this one in particular deserves 5 stars. I've never had such good customer service in a consistent manner as I have from this store. I've seen it go through 3 store managers and the most recent 2 have been awesome. The only reason I would consider giving them a 4 out of 5 (but I'm not) is because their delivery service is somewhat poor, in my opinion. Drives have been, on occasion, abrasive, or they've gotten lost or something like that. All in all, though, this store creates excellent quality pizza combined with good customer service and I would definitely recommend them.

I have a feeling this is Cherry Hill's treasured sushi restaurant; nearly all the tables were reserved for the Friday night 7pm dinner crowd. We just happened to pop in very early evening. Try the Nigiri platter for a good variety of rolls and sashimi. On the hot side, the steamed gyoza were piping hot and delicate, and the poke appetizer had a nice kick.

The hot lattes rival the other gourmet coffee places in the area (Barista Parlor!), but with better prices. Large latte for $4! They also have Vietnamese coffee on the regular menu, which is a great and unique addition that nowhere else has (besides Vietnamese restaurants). Sadly, it's got an odd flavor. I've ordered it several times and it hasn't hit the spot. I'm a huge Vietnamese coffee fan and really love that they include it on the menu, so I'll still give them props for that! I got the yogurt parfait once and it was really nice. A pretty big bowl full of goodness and granola.

Hubby, kids and myself went in on a Tuesday night for dinner. We sat by the sushi bar since we didn't want to do habachi. Kids ordered rice with chicken, took a little long. Hubby and I ordered sushi rolls. I ordered the Hawaiian roll and it was delicious! The reason I'm giving it 4 stars is because of the service. She had a hard time. Also service was slow and it wasn't that busy. I don't have issues going back and giving the service another opportunity since the sushi was so good.

GREAT brisket, pork butt. Hot link was also good. Loved the greens, Cole slaw was standard. Looking forward to coming back to try smoked 

Back with my daughter...we did pick 3 to split and added a side. Brusque is on point as usual!

For dinner they offer crab legs and prime rib along with all the other things. Dessert is nothing to brag about. Puddings, dry cakes, fruit, and ice cream. If you want pop or tea add on $2.50 to the about $21.00 dinner. Normally I would rate them higher, but tonight there were two kids who belonged to one or two of the waitresses and they continuously ran and yelled and drove me crazy.

The pho ga wasn't that impressive. It was nowhere near the best that I've had but I did like that they give you ample lime,  jalapeño etc... I also had com tam with grilled pork and added a fried egg, since this is how I had it in Vietnam. It was really good. You can get grilled pork chop as well.

We're big fans of PDQ, so when I found out the owners were starting WOW I knew it would be good. You can see the similarities in the decor and service (both of which are excellent). We've been twice already, and have sampled the cheeseburger, hot dog, pizza, and taco salad. This is a great fast food place, with more variety then you can get at PDQ. It isn't fancy, and the food isn't fancy, but it's very tasty!

You can tell the staff cares and they're knowledgable about the bean. I'm not a coffee connoisseur myself (I'm learning!) but loved their interesting holiday drink menu, especially these: 

-Spicy Snowman: white chocolate and hot cinnamon
-Mayan Hot Chocolate: vanilla, almond, cinnamon
-Salted Caramel Latte: YUM

I was happy to see that they also offered food, as I tend to camp out in coffee shops for hours on end. I tried the salad and grilled cheese and enjoyed both. The space is nice as well. It's quite large, however the place does get packed.

The pace of service was a little slow but it gave us time to get through the 8 course meal. The dancer was entertaining and added to the experience. The baklava was excellent but the fruit bowl seemed a little underwhelming. Overall it was an enjoyable evening.

The owner is likeable, describing each dish on the menu with a sort of child-like excitement that easily allows the senses to overpower the appetite. Crispy chips and fresh made salsa greet you at your table as your browse the easy-to-read menu. Burritos are over-sized, stuffed with fresh vegetables and a variety of inspiring meats, including shredded chicken, seasoned ground beef, grilled sirloin steak, and pork. Just what the doctor ordered. There are admittedly, many choices for Mexican food on this road, but do yourself a favor and stop in to El Zarape.

I've had the kalbi and bibimbop here which are decent. The neng myun was disappointing. The pajeon and japchae are fine. A decent place to satisfy my Korean cravings once in a while! They also carry classic Korean beers like OB.

**UPDATE**
We went this weekend for brunch, everyone has fried chicken and waffles, which was wonderful. However, I wanted to update this review because I noticed that UC has dropped their prices by $2-$4/entree across the board. The price point seems far more in line with what they're serving now. We will definitely continue coming back. Fantastic use of an old gas station. We sat indoors and both ordered the fried chicken and cucumber Salad. At first we were concerned about the price, $16 fried chicken, however it's worth every penny. It might honestly be the best fried chicken I've ever had. Service was super quick and friendly too. We will definitely be back

If you guys are craving legit Korean food, Choi's now has a kitchen in the back. They make Gimbap, Bibimbap, tofu soup, bulgogi lunch boxes and more. I have literally prayed for years for something like this to happen in Santa Barbara. They may not be the best market, but I don't even care because the food reminds me of L.A.

Now the food. My steamed dumplings were on the bland side and only 4 to a plate for $5. My Bubba roll however, with tempura shrimp was AMAZING! I ate the whole thing. I tasted my hubby's Udon soup aand it was WAY too salty.

The only thing I will say, is that their drinks are more on the sweet side, so if that's not your cup of tea (haha get it??) then I would try playing around with the sugar levels. They also have a decent selection of hot foods if you're craving a snack! My favorite is the spam onigiri. If you're in chinatown I suggest you check this place out!

Overall, I was very happy with my meal! Piping hot, good flavors, and hit the spot. For a moment I felt like I was back in a (much nicer) kimbap cheonguk in Busan...the only thing missing were metal chopsticks.

This place is pretty solid. If you eat pork, the adobada is the best choice hands down. The elote is delish(ask them to cut it off the cobb for you) and the beans aren't bad either. The brisket and steak are great choices. They make the margaritas with fresh lime juice and other fresh ingredients so needless to say they are great.

I didn't think there was good Dim Sum outside of California (excluding Asia), but I was wrong!! Service was great and so was the food! I thoroughly enjoyed everything from shrimp siu mai to scallion pancake to spicy wonton to chicken feet. Chicken feet is not for everyone, but it was good! If you're ever in Philly and craving Dim Sum, I'd recommend Nom Wah.
I had the 'Bowl' option. It came out quick. I did shrimp, lo mein, spicy thai. Veggies we great and I felt like I was eating fresh and good-for-me-food. I'll have to go back again soon!

Top Five Reasons Why You Should Check Out SoHo Cafe & Gallery:

(01) It's right on the Monon Trail. (02) SoHo brews coffee from quality purveyors such as Liberation Roasting and Counter Culture Coffee. (03) The space is HUGE both indoors and outdoors (Psst: there is another room behind the counter for additional seating.)
(04) In addition to coffee and hand-crafted beverages, you can purchase baked goods from Rene's, cake balls from Faith's Cake Ball Factory, ice cream from LICK, and gelato from Palazzolo's (a company from West Michigan). (05) Not only can you get your caffeine fix, but also you can browse and/or purchase artwork and goods for sale from local artisans throughout the shop. In short, SoHo Cafe and Gallery is the spot where you can eat, drink, and shop!

Inventive dishes with delicious ingredients. I'm so happy we decided to give Confluence Kombucha a try. We ordered scrapple, mushroom, and a kimbap taco. All three were ridiculous. I'm not even sure I can pick a favorite.
We love the proprietors just about as much as the food. Definitely making this a weekly treat! (The fresh spring rolls are a family favorite!).
The absolute best fried chicken EVER!!! the sides are also amazing! Mac and cheese and green beans were delicious!!

My husband turned me on to Pho ( pronounced Fuh ) and I had never had Pho before. This is amazingly Delicious. It's very brothy and  has many noodles and veggies and you can choose a meat (eye round or Flank steak or even shrimp... also, most of the Pho bowls come with a Plate of Jalepenos, bean sprouts and Thai Basil sprigs to add extra fmany other selections depending upon the Chef) 

Pho Eden is nice and fairly quiet with very polite staff and they make awesome food. The crispy egg rolls and Fresh spring rolls are big Hits with us. Deeeeelishhhhh.
Ate there on a Sunday morning at 8:30 very full understandable, food came very quick once we got set down I loved the chunky sausage in the gravy my wife had the quiche she enjoyed it very much.

So far everything we've tried has been so good and very fresh. My husband loves menudo and swears by both their red and white menudo. They use shredded chicken breast in their tacos, tostadas and chicken tortilla soup. The chips are homemade and the red salsas come in a mild and hot and are perfect for mixing to your desired heat. Too many good things to say!

Popped in on the way into town for the best tacos I have eaten. Ingredients were fresh and the flavors were complex for the best $9 I have spent on lunch in ages. I had the chicken and spicy beef tacos with a side of elote (spiced grilled corn with cheese). I also tasted my husband's pulled pork taco. These were not cookie cutter tacos and each was deliciously very different.

Been here couple times recently always Very-welcoming Enjoyable Dinners.We All really enjoy the El Trio Appetizer.My Favorite was the Pozole with a Pacifico to drink,The others enjoyed the Chicken Fajitas with Margaritas of course!

The food is authentic and delicious! When we go, we always order the dak bulgogi and my personal favorite, bulgogi. My mother loves the kimchi, but the bbq is my dad's favorite thing to get. We have ordered and tried many items, but we especially like the pork belly and tongue. The service is phenomenal any time we go.
Fresh salads, fresh fish, great marinades and dressing,  seasoning in the meats, amazing garlic knot bread, and baklava that's out of this world.

Ordered the lunch special ($8.95/person), where you can choose a soup or salad (I had the tom yum soup) and an entree. For my entree, I had the hallo bamboo, which had stir-fried bamboo shoots, bell peppers, green beans, and basil - lots of it! I requested it be made spicy (like in Thailand) and when it came out, none of the bites were ever individually "bad" but the cumulative effect was awesome - those were some SPICY peppers they threw in!
Omg what a cute little Asian and French fusion  dessert spot! My boyfriend and I walked over here after eating at Yakitori and ordered the green tea-r-amisu. I also ordered a coffee. It was so yummy!

Hello, South Philly meets southern! Awesome! Classic breakfast items as simple as eggs two ways with toast, to omelettes and veggie burritos are available as well as some "trendier" items such as breakfast egg rolls and salted caramel French toast too. TONS of vegan items as well! Vegan grilled cheese! Very, very good! They have a seasoning that is perhaps a tad spicy for kiddos. Hubs got the breakfast egg rolls and liked them a lot. No skimping on meats and eggs there. They are BYOB so bring the champs and enjoy your mimosas.

Being the only ones in there at the time, the owner made small talk with us, asking how we found it, where we were from, so on. It's actually nice and refreshing when people ask these questions because it means they care about their customers and don't see them as just people coming to give them money. The food was prepared quickly, I had foul and my friend had falafel, we both got an order of grape leaves. Everything is fresh, really fresh, and we could see some of the prep work going on. Probably the best grape leaves I've ever had.

The pizza crust made from their house sourdough starter is our new favorite crust in town. On top of this crust was some serious flavor, wow. Animal potatoes and burger are fantastic. The freaking biscuit. I'm a fan of incredibly dense biscuits, this is one of the best of that style I've had.

I went in looked at their menu, liked it, and sat down. As soon as I did, I was greeted by a lovely assistant. I started off with the golden bags and the escargot for appetizers, and they were amazing. Then I had the special for that day which was sushi grade tuna. This was also very amazing, very juicy, and that sauce; out of this world!

The temperature was perfect on this hot evening. We had an OpenTable reservation and were seated immediately. Our $30 Dining Days meals for the evening were-

GALIA MELON GAZPACHO Fresh Goat Cheese, Basil Oil
ADOBO RUBBED HANGER STEAK Vidalia Onion Rings, Refried Rancho Gordo Cranberry Beans
POTATO GRATIN Andouille, Cabbage, Shaved Cheddar
BEIGNETS Bourbon Butterscotch, Vanilla Mousseline

KESWICK CREAMERY FONDUE Herb Breadsticks
DAY BOAT SCALLOPS Roasted Cauliflower, Sorrel, Orange
SWEET CORN TAGLIATELLE Heirloom Tomato, Local Basil
BEIGNETS Bourbon Butterscotch, Vanilla Mousseline

Each dish was beautifully presented. Every dish was an explosion of interesting flavors. We were not the only diners that felt that way.

THIS place has the best pho I've ever eaten. The broth is incredible. The chicken satay doesn't come with your typical peanut dip, but something like a Panang curry instead. It was different and our table of 3 all loved it. My mom got the coconut soup, and ended up sharing it with me and her boyfriend, not on her terms, but it was just so delicious, we kept "sampling" it!

Rice, bread, onion/tomato/cilantro salad. Really good green sauce. Home made samosa, fluffy and tasty (try with salad and green sauce.)  Stewed potatoes and eggplant. Chicken kadhari on bone, moist. Really good spiced, whole chicken wings.
Best Greek food in town. My favorites are the six onion soup, Mediterranean pizza , moussaka, cannelloni and if the pasticio is in specials. GET IT

We arrived early and decided to hang out at the Graffiti Bar. I had a glass of this year's wine and the boy had a specialty cocktail. We ordered a few items off the happy hour menu and really enjoyed it all - the edamame dumplings, General Tso's chicken soup dumplings, pork bao bun, a Korean barbecue skewer. The bartender was really friendly and the food was brought out very quickly. The great service continued once we were seated in the restaurant. We were able to snag seats at the open kitchen, just like I had requested when making the reservation. It was an added bonus to get to see all of the items being carefully prepared and leaving the kitchen! We ordered more edamame dumplings (they're delicious), tuna rice crackers, kimchee fried rice, and lobster stir fry. We were lucky in that it was still happy hour (it ends at 7 p.m.) so some of these items came at the reduced price. My absolute favorite dish has to be the tuna rice crackers.

The menu was the perfect size to make it easy to decide what to order on your first visit. Portions are sized as Petit, Bistro and Grand with Boards, Hand-Cut Fries and Poutine offerings as well. Our party ordered the French Onion Soup, Hand-Cut Fries, Baby Kale Salad, Roasted Half Chicken, Beef Trio and Ribeye Cap. Presentation of each dish was outstanding and each person at the table was very pleased with their individual dishes and portion size. The cocktail selection seemed plentiful and although I didn't take the time to scan the wine list, I was very pleased with their beer selection.

I am so glad I was finally able to go to this place! I ordered Gimbap and Dukbokki and I almost wasn't able to get a picture of the Gimbap before I ate it all. I bought lots of sweet treats to try and they were all so yummy! I will definitely go there again

Let me start by saying tht if I knew I were going to die tomorrow, the Shrimp and Asparagus Fettuccine with the Safron cream sauce WOULD be my last meal. My wife and I enjoyed every last plate that came our way, from the Calamari appetizer with the homemade marinara sauce, unlike any other marinara sauce you will ever have. After the Calamari was gone, we finished the marinara with the complimentary dinner bread provided, which was freshly baked, then followed our soup minestrone and salad, leaf salad with gorgonzola cheese crumbles and a simple but delicious vinaigrette. My wife had the Gnocchi in pesto sauce, another dish that truly lived up to the hype the roulette dealer at The El Dorado casino played up. By the time the desert came around we were stuffed but one taste of the Florentine and we knew we were definitely leaving with the top button on our pants off!

Small interior but bold and delicious flavors! We tried pot stickers and egg rolls - perfection. Then Kung Pao, sweet and sour chicken, mongolian beef, and chicken chow mein -- all awesome. Great service too.

Everything has a picture. It really helps when you sit there going is that the one I like or is it this one? I went real simple with the Pad See Ew. We were going to a concert that night and I didn't really feel like venturing out of the box. It was middle of the road Pad See Ew, meaning it was exactly as it should have been. I will note that it wasn't too salty which made me very happy. I hate over-salted food!
Excellent BBQ ribs when I dined here couple of months ago. Today I tried their crispy chicken salad. The salad was crisp. The dressing wasn't overpowering.

Delicious, fresh noodles, good prices and plentiful serving sizes. Yummy choices for meat lovers like beef fried noodles and steamed dumplings. And the vegetarian in the family enjoyed their peanut noodles and vegetable noodle soup.

and it's been hard making quick stops to eat. Using yelp, I discovered Terakawa Damen in downtown Philly, and am immensely grateful that I did. My family and I ordered three appetizers, two bowls of udon, one bowl of ramen, and one rice bowl. They all exceeded my expectations. The appetizers were all nicely crisp, the udon full of taste and not messy, the ramen easy to cut with the best pork I've had in awhile, and the rice soft and flavorful. Definitely coming back the next time I visit.

Great selection of tamales! So glad they opened this new location in northwest Tucson! This new facility has a nice large area to sit with a few outside tables as well! Today there is a line out the door due to their grand opening specials. You can eat there or buy frozen tamales for a later date! One of my favorites is the vegan blue made with calabacitas (squash) and blue corn masa! Can't go wrong with any of their salsas either.

I'm a big fan of Thai curries and I have to say this is one of the best Massaman curries I have had and the delicious and unusual addition of a meaty tender lamb shank is genius! Service was attentive and friendly. Beautiful dining room with water feature in the center.

The spring rolls are also really good. I think the drunken noodles I've had here are the best I've ever had. Hubby got the pad see ew and was very pleased too. This is definitely going to be our go to Thai food place on lazy nights!
Great AYE sushi spot, with friendly service. Solid sushi options with fruity,  raw,  and cooked rolls. Also,  has sushi burritos and poke bowl options.

It literally like extended my lifespan by ten years. This is SO GOOD i highly recommend. I was told to get the mongolian noodles after originally deciding on pad see ew, because the mongolian noodles are "like the same thing but with less veggies and Taiwanese sausage" and even though I was trying to be vegetarian I was very intrigued and again I was delusional. despite breaking vegetarianism and further contributing to the demise of our planet as well as to capitalism (bc of that extra dollar for the mongolian noodles vs the pad see ew) I felt like it was maybe worth it. Felt so good. 10/10

We also sat on the patio where the view of the city and sunset was AMAZING! So quick tip, sit on the patio! We got a ton of appetizers: bombas contigo (deep fried potato and bacon croquettes), patatas bravas (potatoes with aioli sauce), ceviche Lima (ahi tuna with chips). The ceviche was definitely the best thing, our table ate it fast! I also loved the potatoes and aioli sauce, so freaking good!

and I'm happy we did. My fiancé got the chicken kabob and he really enjoyed it. I wasn't very hungry so I had kebbeh and dolma's. It was so good that it left me wanting more and I ended up finishing the meal with a piece of baklawa. The price was great and the atmosphere was enjoyable.
Yes I would nick. Love at first bite. And I didn't mention that lobster roll. Very good too.

In my opinion, it is one of the best Indian food places in the area. The butter chicken and palak paneer is amazing. LOVE the buffet, always pleasantly surprised when I try a new dish. They also offer take out buffet containers when I'm in the mood for take out but do not want to spend tons of money on different indian dishes.
I had their most popular red curry dish. Definitely one of the best curry dishes I've ever had, not to mention affordable. Great service, great atmosphere.

The place is decorated with a funky graffiti styled wall that fits the laid back atmosphere. It's the ideal setting for grabbing a comforting bowl of noodles. The foooood: the menu offers so much variety (ramen, dan dan noodles, coconut curry - it was tough to choose!) I settled on the miso ramen bc I wanted savory, and it was so delicious. I added the bok choy for sake of veggies, but my dish still had the most meat I've ever seen in a ramen bowl. Most of the ramen that I've had tends to come with pork belly over pork shoulder, so I wasn't sure what to expect, but the pork shoulder added a new texture without losing any flavor!

Ordered some Pad Thai for lunch from this place and it was very tasty. I have just begun my venture into Pad Thai but there take on the dish wasn't as refined as other places I've had but for the price point you can't beat it. Not very spicy but next time I will ask for extra spice. My only complaint is the amount of protein given in an order, but other than that this is one of my new go to's.
If you're a fan of beef satay, you need to try this pho.The tastiest I've had in Edmonton and I've tried many. The salad roles also taste great.
The crab with egg white fried rice is amazing. Kung Pao Shrimp - not super hot - and crispy egg rolls are our go-tos, but really they're just supporting players to the fried rice.

Excited to go back and try everything but it may be impossible to not get their Nashville chicken sandwich. Its perfect. Their tempura cauliflower and pumpkin appetizer was perfectly cooked, creative, and delicious.

KHAAAAN! I normally associate the name Khan with Indian/Pakistanis , but this is an Iraqi joint. While they serve traditional Middle Eastern dishes like kebabs, etc, I was very curious in trying the Masgouf, hailed as the national dish of Iraq. It is a roast and grilled Carp seasoned with salt/pepper/tamarind. The dish as presented in the restaurant was served on a bed of rice and with sliced fresh tomatoes and bell peppers.

I went through a phase (probably a year or so when I lived closer to CH) where I only ordered this salad. If you like Mediterranean salads this one is a MUST. 3- when I feel in the mood, the short rib risotto is also good, but you need to have it with red wine and be ready for a full comfort food belly afterwards. Now don't get me wrong I like a lot of menu items- but those three pending my mood are my usual go to's. Also- wine club is fun.

It was a hot day and I am so happy this place has a good A/C system. That cooled me down a lot. I ordered the bbq pork and duck over rice. I thought it was excellent. It's a good place for good chinese food.

Nice weather and people watching. Yes please. I ordered the coq au vin crepe. I've never eaten coq au vin but I thought what the heck. The minute I took the first bite I knew I was in trouble. There was no way I would have leftovers.

Will definitely be returning. Good, fast service and I loved my Massaman Curry - wonderful flavors. Pad Thai was a bit spicy for my taste. Curry was plenty enough to box up and finish for lunch the next day.

The food was excellent. I had the tagliatelle in the large portion and it was definitely a lot of food. I saved some space for dessert and had the peach tart with EVOO gelato, it was bomb. Our waiter was extremely attentive and on point to where u would blink and your glass was suddenly filled with water, he was awesome! I would definitely recommend this spot if you are in the mood for something different from the seafood and other common foods you'll find everywhere in New Orleans.

I am so glad they took us here. The chicken tchoupitoulas was moist, tender, had a nice kick of cayenne and the dirty rice was the perfect side for it. Add on the bread pudding and the chocolate souffle and I was in heaven. Next time, I need that cajun martini. Looks incredible.
Evan was so helpful and the food was amazing. Would definitely do it again the next time I'm in town. I love ice cream! Henry

Really good Italian restaurant in St Pete. Great view and outside seating, but even better service (Thank You Jessie!!!). We started with some bruschetta and sangria, the bruschetta was fantastic and fresh. We all ordered seafood, so we ordered a rosé (a Scalabrone recommended by Jessie- which was really good). I tried the lobster Mac and cheese, and the far diavolo, both were full of seafood fantastic.

For dinner we had the short ribs, the hanger steak, and the meatballs + the wedge salad. All were excellent. Finally, for dinner we had the chocolate lava cake, cheesecake and smores. All were good, but the chocolate lava cake was the best of the bunch.

This restaurant is run by the daughter of the owner of a chain of the same restaurants in Taiwan. All of the Taiwanese dishes are flavorful and truly unique to Taiwanese style of cooking. Highly recommend the scallion pancake, beef noodle soup, 3-cup/ flavor chicken, pot-stickers, Shanhaigh Won Ton Soup, and Taiwanese pork meat ball, and oyster pancake.

The first time I went here, I was quite impressed. I was with my Chinese friend, who chatted up the staff. We were all very excited for dim sum all day, and everything I tried was awesome (pan fried scallion cake, pork congee, and shanghai soup dumplings. That experience deserved four stars. However, the second time I went, I had the worst sesame chicken of my life.

The food is good for a lower priced place. Not excellent food, and they are charging excellent food prices. We ordered:
2,2,2 oysters 
Escargot bordelaise
French onion soup
Crawfish bisque 
Wedge with roquefort 
Coq au vin
Chicken rochumbeau 
No dessert and 2 cocktails  well 3 but one was so bad we didnt drink it and the lime was old. They immediately apologized and replaced the drink. Which we paid for.but personal taste hated it anyway. "No. There's bound to be something better on the menu" said my companion. I tasted hers, she's right the coq au vin beats it. Really good food but again priced on par with the culinary superstars of new Orleans and they dont measure up.

Love all their gluten free options: frozen crab cake, frozen crab legs, frozen New England clam chowder. Sometimes they have a coconut shrimp special ready to be heated in the oven. Located in a shopping plaza.

Please do get a reservation first. But we didn't and just waited and in about 20 minutes we got seated! I forgot to take a picture of the lavender cheesecake but it was crazy good. Very different but good! The scallops were fabulous.

As every Sunday I ordered my really big breakfast, I asked for cheese on my eggs. I got my food along with my boyfriends food, I didn't have any cheese on my eggs so I told my waitress, she took my plate. 30 minutes went by and still I did not get my food back & there was no sign of it coming anytime soon, now at this point I don't want the food anymore. My waitress then came and told me she took my meal off the bill, which was obvious because I didn't get the food to begin with. I work in the food business & when something like that were to happen a manager would come and apologize for the inconvenience & offer the entire bill to be paid, a free meal in the future or something along those lines, But nothing at all.

Went here on a Wednesday with my friend for lunch hoping  it would be good. We ordered food that came out pretty fast but there were a few caviets. The pork congee barely had any pork in it, mostly just rice, and it lacked a lot of flavor. We asked for water and we didn't get it until half way / 75% way through our meal. The waitress was too busy talking to her coworkers up front to see us waving and trying to get her attention multiple times. Then at the end we asked for boxes for 3 separate dishes plus the congee which is a soup like. And she said "use one box don't waste" I was like " no were going to need 2 more boxes." Then she says rudely "ok I know!" then comes back with one. Then we had to ask her a 3rd time.

Of course we found it on yelp and yelp had delivered once again. Beef noodle soup is one of the best I've had (including the dozens of places I've been to in LA). The scallion pancake comes with a special sauce that flavors it just right. The oyster pancake is very authentic. They even have boba milk tea....i would rate it a strong A-.

I called at 6:30 p.m. to order Chinese broccoli - it was sold out again! I ordered the shrimp and vegetable sampler and chicken chow fun. The portions were huge and it was only for me! The food was hot, flavorful and delicious.

The menu was not creative, especially for us vegetarians. And overpriced, over fried, yada yada yada. The best part of the meal was the warm bread with oil drizzle for dipping, and the minestrone soup. If we had stopped there we would have been so much happier than trying to indulge in entrees. My husband had the shrimp Parmesan, he couldn't finish his meal because of the cloyingly heavy batter.

I'm in agreement with fellow yelper Jim, this place is perfect if you want good mexican food but not the expensive seating or your grabbing to go. Food is great. I had carne asada burritos that were yummy and my buddy ordered the chile relleno and cheese enchilada. If you want the truly hot salsa, you have to ask for it cause they keep it away from the gringos.

Doused in bbq sauce, the dish is a satisfactory one due largely to the very good sauce. But certainly this is still not a good representation of true  bbq brisket. One more comment:  I love good cornbread. But why is it so hard to find good cornbread in Tucson. Here at Mr. K's and at some other bbq joints, the cornbread is almost unrecognizable as such. It might be my bias from having lived in Texas and Carolinas, but I like my cornbread coarse in texture and, most important, taste of corn. It is not that difficult to make..

They offer a respectable buffet of North Indian foods: unlimited naan, rice, salad, vegetables, legumes, chicken, and fruit for $10.99. At this restaurant I recommend their tikka masala. I also enjoy the daal, chana masala, and aloo gobi. If they had vegetable samosas or gulab jamun as I've eaten at other buffets, I would be coming here a lot more often though! I was disappointed when the restaurant moved the naan from the traditional basket of fresh offerings at the table to in the buffet line, but it still tastes the most authentic in town.
Or at least to me! Staff was great and made me feel very welcome. I had the short rib grilled cheese... YUM! It was delicious.

Zero star if I could for kitchen service. Order didn't come until half an hour later. And it's only a simple soon tofu jjigae. People who ordered after me got their orders in 10 minutes. Agree with other reviewerd that this place is not even closely as good as it was in 2010.

After pondering and decoding the large menu in front of me, I settled on a "coldstone creation" or whatever nonsense they call it. When I was paying, the women who took my order (3 times), and made my order, had the nerve to tell me that two small ice creams costed 12 dollars. While the ice cream they serve is certainly no hand made gelato, and that they could not compensate me for not being able to complete my order twice, I gawked at the price out loud making sure everyone in line could hear. Cold stone creamery serves over sugared dairy product laced with candy to appeal to us Americans who find it alright to be charged 6 dollars for a small ice cream. The corporation as a whole ruins the lives of its franchisees and is incapable of making their wrongs, right.

Incredible selection of wine. We chose a Duckhorn Pinot Noir. Desserts of creme brulee and lava cake washed down with warm snifters of grand marnier. Our server, Saughn was professional and efficient without being overbearing. Offered samples of wine, and couldn't have been more accomodating.

Great waterfront ambience with decent tune-age from Thursday night's musician setting the mood. Blood orange margherita was delicious. For my entree, I had the chicken caprese pasta, in which I found the warm seasoned chicken slices conflicting with the cold and large Predator-dreadlock-sized pesto-covered pasta noodles a bit lacking for the price. All in all I was happy with the experience and our waitress was right on cue. Would visit again.

The tempura is crisp and yummy. The sukiyaki is showy and fun, with a tempting broth and delicious vegetables. The sushi rice is perfect, and the sashimi is always good, with authentic ingredients and decent prices. Now for the bad: the service can be exceptionally slow at times, though the ladies are always kind. The fried rice is greasy and unpalatable (I stick with steamed).

Can I have my $10 and 4,321 calories back, please? The first thing I asked the staff was if their brisket was fatty or lean. "Oh, we cut off all the fat for you," they said. They lied. There was more fat on my scratch biscuit than meat. The brisket had little flavor, and the horseradish mayo had zero bite. Shame, because the decor is pretty cute and it's a fun concept. Pass.

Savory and numbing but so satisfying these noodles appears unassuming until mixed with all the pepper corns coming to the top... A habit forming dish. For the mains we ordered the Mapo Tofu. A bowl of spicy, fragrant silken tofu in a thick and amazingly complex sauce. I make this favorite at home but can't even hope to emulate the complexity of flavors in this iconic dish.

I ordered the BiBibop and it was very dry and the food had little flavor. The seaweed soup was very salty, almost to the point you couldn't eat it. Other people in my group had the seafood soft tofu stew and the dumpling soup. The seafood soft tofu stew wasn't very good, the tofu wasn't soft and silky, not very good flavor. The dumpling soup had no flavor. Not a very good place to go to if you aren't planning to do all you can eat.

Terrible. They can't even do sesame chicken, let alone "eight treasure duck." The duck may actually be roadrunner, not sure. The lo mein tastes like a rank cigar. Really, it's that bad. On another note, took an hour to deliver a block up the road.

As always the place was spotless and cheery and the staff cordial and knowledgeable. I am a fan of Yolks  mouth watering pancakes, bacon and coffee. My son raved about the Nutella crepes and my husband devoured his eggs over easy plater. The portions were generous, my coffee was refilled frequently and we look forward to stopping in again soon!

The first time I started with a selection hummus and it was very good. My entree was the lamb shank and it fell right off the bone, yum. The second time I took advantage of the prefix dinner including octopus starter, moussaka entree and baklava to finish. It was very, very good and 35 bucks a good price too. I would recommend this raunt for foodies, dates or business dinner.
Do not let the looks fool you. The food is absolutely delicious. Had spicy Hunan beef, great hot and sour soup and a tasty egg roll. If you're near the St Louis airport, eat here. Cash Only.

I can truly say I've never had a better French onion soup. The broth was delectable and I wish I could have had a large pot of it. Other beautiful mentions include the escargot. I love the hefty amount of fresh garlic. "Mmmmm garlic" - Homer Simpson voice.

The host for the event whips up vegetarian curry as well as free ice cream! This is definitely a great free event and great venue. With low priced drinks and plentiful seating, this is a great place to stop in if you are having dinner nearby at Kebab or St Roch market. They have a number of great paid and free events like their shows and their free swing dancing as well. Check it out at least once and choose for yourself!

Anyhoooo, Met a dear friend and her sons, plus a few of her friends who brought their friends here for dinner. We were treated to a plethora of dishes, ranging from shrimp shumi, kimchi pajun, tons of banchans, tangsooyuk, teriyaki, yukgaejang, and of course..4 types of bbq. Brisket, bulgogi, kalbi, and samgyeopsal. The meats were delicious, and I was happy they served it with red leaf lettuce, doenjang, and surprisingly sesame oil with pepper. Though no green onion salad - didn't wind up asking for it because we had so much food already.

The mac n cheese had a nerve to be a knock off kraft (the blue box blues), the brocoli was the best tasting thing in the entire platter. I also ordered the mega fries with wiz, mozzarella,  and bacon...the wiz was extremely heavy which killed it for me, oh! And they gave me pita bread which was greasy and looked like someone picked at it...$22.oo wasted...don't even bother, if I wasn't at work and had a car,  I would have got my money back

The food was amazing! The maple bourbon pork chop was the best pork chop I have ever had. We tried an array of things from the chicken noodle soup, to a grilled cheese, hamburger, and a salad. We all kept raving about how great everything was. I could go back and order the pork chop every night!

I called to price tamale masa and was put on hold for 10 minutes then they hung up on me. I called back and nicely asked the same question and lady told me "We don't give prices over the phone". Worst customer service I have ever experienced by a store.

I really think the people commenting and giving the low stars dont know much about vietnamese cuisine... Anyways, I also had the eggs rolls which were also made just the way my mom made them, they were delicious. I also had the bbq pork banh mi, the bread was crispy and tasted good along with the bbq pork. The portion size was good too for the price. Because it's inside KOP mall you would expect it to be more americanized but it does taste good and hopefully more people decide to try it out!

It was one of our favorite meals of the trip! It's obvious they take great pride in their tradition of amazing food and service. Started with a pitcher of red sangria, split the salad, then enjoyed Seafood Paella and Stuffed Grouper for entrees. Everything was very flavorful and out of this world. Especially loved the rice, perfectly baked grouper, and sauce.

Today I wanted some Pho, but wanted it to go. My husband picked it up got home and noticed they gave us the wrong order. He called to find out what happen to our order, they said there were orders with the same name so to come back to get our order.

They brought out us a sample of their chicken skewers, grilled perfectly (see pics). To top it off they got wind it was my hubby's B-day, they sang Happy Birthday and brought him cake!! (Peanut butter cheesecake) 

At the end I'd highly recommend this place to anyone who appreciates high quality Italian pizza or just in the mood for some good Italian grub..... Bon Appetit!!

I've been getting takeout from here for the past 2 months, and every single item I've ordered tasted fresh and delicious. Some of the favorite items i get are:
-Shrimp Tempura dinner - crispy and crunchy, comes with soup and salad. The miso soup here is very good and has a lot of flavor. -Kani su salad - I haven't seen this in many places and it's delicious. It's kani mixed in a sweet and sour vinegar sauce. I love it. -UFO roll - fried kani in a spicy sauce
-Magic roll - shrimp tempura roll w/ tobiko and crunch. If they keep the quality up every single time, I think this place will be my go-to sushi spot.

Overpriced, poor quality food. $19 hamburger tasted like frozen patties. The fries were cold and soggy, the ribs were dry and tough like jerky. The $45 steak was small and over cooked. The steak had no taste and was swimming in grease.

Decent. Wouldn't recommend going here if you're vegetarian or dairy free. Your only options are a handful of veggies, a sushi roll, rice, and veggie lo mein. Picked through chicken and broccoli just to get some broccoli. Other than that, everything else was fine.

Very good meal the other night for dinner. Decided to try it out because the Chris Stevens Band plays there and they recommend it. Tuna app was great, bolognese was HUGE and my wife enjoyed the crab cakes. We sat outside and it was a cool evening. Fans were a nice touch.

I arrived at Xiandu slightly early and was worried I'd have to wait, but good news! My order was ready to go! The dishes we had were the Chicken Pad Thai ($13) and Kal Soi Gai ($14) The Pad Thai was a huge portion that could easily feed two people, but the real standout was the Kal Soi (think creamy coconut soup with perfect ramen noodles and a little bit of spice). I would absolutely recommend Xiandu to my friends, family, coworkers, etc -- the food was incredible.

The location is afterall in the heart of the Vietnamese community and you know it's good when the same ethnic group eat there. The menu has a huge selection to almost everything to viet cuisines. I'm never disappointed in the countless amount of times I've been there but two weeks ago, I was very disappointed on their simple dish of grilled lemongrass chicken with broken rice. The chicken was so dry, to the point where I had a hard time swallowing it. Perhaps, it was an old batch of marinated chicken.

They have a large variety of items on their menu, many things that you don't see everywhere. They also have a selection of Americanized Chinese dishes. I had the shrimp with garlic sauce and then orange chicken on my second visit. The shrimp with garlic sauce was fine, not _amazing_, but not bad. It was served with veggies & mushrooms. The orange chicken was **outstanding**! A light batter and very fresh and tasty, with orange peel and miniature dried hot peppers in the sauce, just like it should have. There was also plenty of broccoli and peppers.

Nicer than some other vietnamese restaurants in terms of decor. I sat in a booth, and every time the guy in the booth behind me sat back, it would bump me. Other than that, i got the combo broken rice. It came with egg, crab cake, bbq pork chop, shredded pork and a few picked veggies. In addition, it came with a few grilled shrimp!
I've been there a few times. The ill-named 50/50 burger (so-called b/c is half beef and half pork belly). I also life the salt and pepper wings and the lo mein is fantastic.

My wife and I went to breakfast there on Monday morning, we found the waiters and hostesses very friendly and very helpful. We found the food;  I had the chicken fried steak and my wife had fruit crepes to be very tasty. The decor was okay and the hot chocolate drinks were excellent. My only complaint is that the chicken fried steak I had was over cooked.

This is my fav authentic vietnamese restaurant in Philly & South Jersey area. They have very healthy & phenomenal foods. I love Bun Cha Hanoi, its Vietnamese vermicelli with porks, vege... Chicken Pho is also a great choice, one of the most delicious fresh Chicken in this area. For the drink, Matcha Latte is #1 

Go & try it!

The food is reasonably price. There was a nice variety for different types. I had the shawarma and it was good. The fried shrimp reminds me of the times I was in New Orleans with the hush puppy on the side. The chicken kabob was moist and seasoned nicely.

You receive an entire tables worth of traditional Korean condiments, many of them fermented veggies. This was great as you could create your own lettuce wrap. We also ordered the kimchi scallion pancake which was large and tasty, but it wouldn't be at the top of my list to order again. Rice Market is not cheap by any means, but I think it's great value for the quality and the experience of feeling like a badass grilling your own meat over searing hot coals.

The place wasn't crowded so not sure why he disappeared but he did. Not satisfied with the service at all. We ordered the Chipotle BBQ wings and the heirloom & cucumber gazpacho. The gazpacho was one of the specials and was delicious. Perfect starter for a hot summer night. The wings were tasty and very large and the sauce was good and not too spicy.

Really good! Pictures is the margherita pizza- half +pepperoni, half +garlic. Also had the breadsticks - in the words of the server- like pizza crusts (good for me when it's made of that delicious dough!). And started with the Italian caesar - which was fine but mild.
Everything we've tried here is delicious! Some of our favorites are the Spaghetti Carbonara, Chefs Special Pasta and their Calzones!
I always get the bulgogi dolsot. It's always the safe choice. When they bring it to you, you can still hear everything sizzling.

The decor is modern and not over done Asian. The menu has several dishes featuring duck. The duck crepes are different but simple and good. They were under-staffed for the amount of business they had. The staff did a good job trying to keep up.

My wife and I visited Pastries N Chaat for  the daily lunch thali. We chose the vegetarian option as we are vegetarian. The thali consisted of yellow dal, veg of the day(ridge gourd beerakaya on this day), salad, rice( which was amazing), fresh chapati, samosa and a gulab jamun. The yellow dal, though simple, was uniquely flavored and delicious. The ridge-gourd was hot and spicy and cooked with tomato. You would think that rice is just a ubiquitous addition to a thali but the rice was a stand out. The rice was cooked with whole spices like cardamon pods and cloves and was flavorful and addictive. The samosa was spiced nicely and crisply fresh. The chapati was fresh and hot. The gulab jamun was an excellent end to the meal.

I ordered the kickin crab soup/power salad & couldn't get over the size of both. And to top it off, they were both excellent tasting! The soup had such flavor that I would go back again & get the same thing!

The St Chuck Duck sandwich is divine, especially if you get it with the cheese grits (this coming from a woman who has hated grits all her life). The Buddha's Temptation, apricots wrapped in bacon and drizzled with a sweet savory sauce, is truly divine and not to be missed. The guacamole is quite good, and this is the only place outside of my mom's kitchen that I will order gumbo and be satisfied with it. The place is clean and lived in and I've never had an issue with staff. It's right on the streetcar line, too.

This restaurant is the reincarnation of a restaurant I used to to before it suffered a fire and closed The old restaurant was good the reincarnation is great I tried a test ordering my favorite dish Osso Buco it was out of sight I've gone to all the Italian restaurants in Philly but this place is as good as the best To top it off it is dirt cheap Two Hendricks Osso Buco Tiramisu Double Expresso Grappa The bill was $40 Try to top that You don't have to order Osso Buco You can order pasta and meat balls That's what its abbreviated name stands for Meatballs and More Ciao Bella!
We ordered other things. A few minutes later  our food came out fresh, delicious. This was probably the best burger and reasonably priced. So clean. So friendly really nice place!!!!!
Drunken noodles! It's hard to sometimes choose, but their drunken noodle and coconut soup are my comfort food craving--they always, always hit the spot!! Yum!

Food was delicious - ratatouille and spaghetti squash were really tasty. Ratatouille had fresh thyme and I think tarragon. Cookie was perfect texture and flavor profile. Food is excellent and salads look like they have improved.

At night, they switch to a menu brimming with choices for meat eaters (chicken and lamb abound) and vegetarians alike. The owners have renovated and the interior ambiance is welcoming and much more swanky than you'd expect for an old shopping center on Nolensville Road. Some of our favorites: creamy yogurt sauced Navratan Korma, Daal Makhani, spicy Chicken Vindaloo, and Garlic Naan. Although, truthfully, in over a dozen visits, we've never had a terrible dish, so you can't really go wrong!

Enjoyed the Tonkotsu! This is my new go to ramen spot in New Orleans. The staff was very friendly and he service was on point. Went to the soft opening and even though they were busy, they took care of my table. The eggs came out at a perfect boil and flavors hit the right spot. I highly recommend this place for anyone who is looking for the hottest Ramen spot in town.

So this place is like taking a trip in a time machine....seriously so 1960's Chinese! The waiters are in white shirts and tuxedo bow ties, the menu is EXTENSIVE and it is soooooo delicious! The crab ragoon and fried wontons are to die for, the General Tso's chicken is delicious with all white meat! Go there its awesome!

Their spicy shrimp rolls were also absolutely delicious. I don't recommend getting the fried rice; it tastes like regular rice loaded with soy sauce. The wonton appetizers are also very good. I love the ambiance of this place at night; they have good modern music playing, and it's very lively. If you like quiet dinners, this place is not for you.
